{
  "local_port": 34616,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best books about the late-80s/90s internet industry leading up to the dot-com bubble?",
  "response": "The late 1980s and 1990s were pivotal decades for the internet industry, culminating in the dot-com bubble of the late 1990s and its subsequent burst in the early 2000s. Several books capture this era's innovation, hype, and eventual reckoning. Here are some of the best books about the internet industry during this period:\n\n---\n\n### **Historical and Analytical Accounts**\n1. **\"The New New Thing: A Silicon Valley Story\" by Michael Lewis**  \n   Focuses on Silicon Valley during the 1990s, particularly the rise of Netscape and its founder, Jim Clark. Lewis provides a vivid narrative of the era's entrepreneurial spirit and technological ambition.\n\n2. **\"Dot.Con: The Greatest Story Ever Sold\" by John Cassidy**  \n   A critical examination of the dot-com bubble, exploring the economic, cultural, and technological forces that drove the frenzy and its inevitable collapse.\n\n3. **\"Dealers of Lightning: Xerox PARC and the Dawn of the Computer Age\" by Michael Hiltzik**  \n   While primarily about the 1970s and 1980s, this book provides essential context for the innovations that shaped the internet industry in the 1990s.\n\n4. **\"Nerds 2.0.1: A Brief History of the Internet\" by Stephen Segaller**  \n   Based on the PBS documentary series, this book offers a comprehensive history of the internet's development from its early days to the dot-com boom.\n\n---\n\n### **Personal Memoirs and Insider Perspectives**\n5. **\"The Silicon Boys and Their Valley of Dreams\" by David A. Kaplan**  \n   A lively account of the people and companies that shaped Silicon Valley during the 1990s, offering insights into the culture and personalities behind the tech boom.\n\n6. **\"Startup: A Silicon Valley Adventure\" by Jerry Kaplan**  \n   A firsthand account of founding Go Corporation, a pioneering pen-computing company, and the challenges of navigating the tech industry during the 1990s.\n\n7. **\"Accidental Empires: How the Boys of Silicon Valley Make Their Millions, Battle Foreign Competition, and Still Can't Get a Date\" by Robert X. Cringely**  \n   A humorous and insightful look at the rise of the personal computer and internet industries, focusing on the personalities and egos that drove innovation.\n\n---\n\n### **Cultural and Economic Perspectives**\n8. **\"The Dot-Com Bubble\" by Brent Schlender**  \n   Part of the \"Turning Points\" series, this book provides a concise overview of the dot-com bubble, its causes, and its consequences.\n\n9. **\"The Search: How Google and Its Rivals Rewrote the Rules of Business and Transformed Our Culture\" by John Battelle**  \n   While primarily focused on the rise of Google, this book offers valuable context for the dot-com era and its aftermath.\n\n10. **\"Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush Years on the Internet\" by Michael Wolff**  \n    A candid memoir about starting an internet company during the dot-com boom and the challenges of surviving in an overhyped industry.\n\n---\n\n### **Fiction and Satire**\n11. **\"Microserfs\" by Douglas Coupland**  \n    A novel that captures the culture of the tech industry in the 1990s, focusing on the lives of Microsoft employees and their struggles with identity and ambition.\n\n12. **\"The First $20 Million Is Always the Hardest\" by Po Bronson**  \n    A satirical novel about the startup culture of Silicon Valley in the 1990s, exploring the absurdities of the tech world.\n\n---\n\n### **Post-Bubble Reflections**\n13. **\"Dot Bomb: My Days and Nights at an Internet Goliath\" by J. David Kuo**  \n    A memoir by a former employee of the failed e-commerce startup Value America, offering a firsthand account of the dot-com bubble's excesses.\n\n14. **\"Dot Complicated: Untangling Our Wired Lives\" by Randi Zuckerberg**  \n    While primarily about the broader impact of technology, this book includes insights into the dot-com era and its lasting influence.\n\n---\n\nThese books collectively provide a multifaceted view of the internet industry during its formative years, offering historical context, personal stories, and critical analysis of the era's triumphs and failures.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
